  <title>Examples of fractals</title>
  <introduction>
  
<p>There are an endless number of interesting fractals and in many cases
a variety of mechanisms of generating a particular fractal.</p>


  </introduction>
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-sierpinski-triangle">
    <title>Typical construction</title>
<p> The Sierpinski triangle can be constructed by shading an inverted
triangle in the middle of each white triangle.</p>
<p>    <title></title>
<figure xml:id="fig-320">
	<caption>Top left: Step 0 is an upright white triangle. Top right: Step 1 contains an
	inverted, shaded triangle in the center of what was 'Step 0'. Bottom left: Step 2
	contains all of the triangles present in 'Step 1', but adds three
	shaded, inverted triangles in the white space of 'Step 1'.  Bottom Right: Step 3 (and
	onward) is more of the same.</caption>
