<title>Calculating Numbers of Triangles</title>
<introduction><p>With a bit of careful guessing, it's possible to
explore formulas that support these patterns and that allow us to
predict what happens as the number of steps increases (beyond our
drawing ability).</p></introduction>

<p>How can we relate the numbers of
each type of triangle and the total to the step number? Looking at the
white triangle numbers, you might notice that the number increases by a
factor of three each step.  In fact, if we let <m>W_{k}</m> be
the number of white triangles on step <m>k</m>, <me>W_{k}=3^{k}</me>. 
If we went to Step 10, we would expect <m>W_{10} =
3^10</m>, which is <m>59,049</m> white triangles!</p>

